TAR 295: Family Tax Credit rate and (single-tier) abatement options with comparison to pre- and post-indexation status quo settings

[BUDGET-SENSITIVE]

Note: This report is best viewed with Google Chrome. Please press and hold the “Ctrl” key, and then press the “-” or “+” keys on the keyboard, to zoom-out or zoom-in.

Summary

TAR 291 thoroughly canvassed a broad range of one- and two-tier Working for Families abatement setting and per child rate increases for the Family Tax Credit. This enabled the selection of several potential settings on the “child poverty reduction frontier” that achieved the highest poverty reductions for given fiscal costs, while also avoiding bringing new families into AHC50 poverty, or making families already in AHC50 poverty worse off, which were issues for the more redistributive options in TAR 286. Ministers have ruled out the two-tiered abatement options, and have indicated an interest in the lower fiscal cost single-tier options.

Although TAR 291 did explore all combinations in a grid of FTC rate increases and abatement rates, detailed analysis, including distributional analysis, was only done for a few 1-tier options. This TAR provides this detailed analysis for a few more low-cost 1-tier settings.

EMTR plots, similar to those produced in TAR 291 – part 6, will also be supplied in a separate TAR (296).

Some observations

  • The fiscal and poverty outputs have already been covered in previous analysis; the only new aspect here is the addition of the 95% margin of error for the three scenarios not previously modelled in detail. These uncertainties are significant, particularly for the poverty metrics.

  • The household and family winners and losers plots show that

    • most losing households are in the fourth household equivalised disposable income (HEDI) decile
    • for all settings the average gains for gaining households increase steadily with decreasing HEDI
    • for all settings HEDI deciles 1, 3, and 4 have the most gaining households.
    • when assessed against the pre-indexation status quo, losses are less noticeable, and for some settings they disappear. Also, gains are noticeable right up to the top decile – probably due to Best Start indexation.
    • there is a striking similarity between the post-indexation winner and loser distributions of the $5/27% option and the $7.50/28%, though obviously the magnitude of gains and losses is greater in the latter.
    • for the $5/27% and $7.50/28% options, in total, less WFF spending (after indexation) is going to the population with family taxable income over $100k. However, with the FTC/BSTC indexation included the total change in spend is still positive for this population.

Outputs

For tax year 2022-23, using HES20/IDI input, the BEFU21 forecast and the settings in the table below:

  1. Standard TAWA outputs, including fiscal costs, poverty metrics, and winners and losers by household equivalised disposable income (HEDI) deciles with respect to a post- FTC/BSTC indexation status quo.
  2. Winners and losers by household equivalised disposable income (HEDI) deciles with respect to a pre- FTC/BSTC indexation status quo.
  3. Winning and losing families by family taxable income bins ($10k steps up to $140k, and under/over $100k, as per TAR 292) with respect to a post- FTC/BSTC indexation status quo.
  4. Winning and losing families by family taxable income bins ($10k steps up to $140k, and under/over $100k, as per TAR 292) with respect to a pre- FTC/BSTC indexation status quo.

Scenarios

The options considered here are all have a single-tier of abatement, with the abatement threshold set at its current value of $42,700. Only the per-child rate of FTC payment, and the abatement rate are varied. The options are:

Weekly per-child FTC increase ($) Abatement Rate (%)
5.0 25 (current)
5.0 26
5.0 27
7.5 27
7.5 28

Modelling assumptions

  1. This analysis was carried out using Treasury’s micro-simulation model of the tax and welfare system - TAWA. All calculations should be considered as estimations.
  2. Estimates are for the 2022/2023 tax year using HES 2019/20 augmented using IDI data, inflated and population adjusted with BEFU 2021 inflation estimates. Results are sensitive to particular data and EFU inflation estimates, and TAWA routinely updates its data and EFU inflation estimates. This can result in differences when comparing analysis requests.
  3. Status quo results correspond to the currently legislated tax and welfare system.
  4. The modified OECD equivalisation scale is used to calculate equivalised incomes.
  5. The depth of a household in poverty is the amount of (unequivalised) income required to bring the income of the household to the poverty threshold. Households with negative incomes were adjusted to have zero income for the purpose of calculating depth.
  6. The same quartile boundaries (based on all households) are used in each winners & losers table.
  7. A take-up rate (a model based on admin recipients) has been applied to the Accommodation Supplement when the expected number of recipients changes. Recipients are in the first case based on receipt in the admin data.
  8. Apparent inconsistencies in totals are due to rounding and/or suppression, with estimates being suppressed if they did not meet the confidentiality requirements of Statistics NZ.
  9. TAWA does not extend eligibility for core benefits, so individuals who may become newly eligible due to rate and abatement changes will not be included in these results.
  10. Our reporting uses 95% confidence intervals, calculated as the estimate plus or minus the margin of error (MoE). The MoE is a way of measuring statistical uncertainty, it is calculated as 1.96 multiplied by the standard error of the estimate.

Risk/reliability assessment

Due to the impact of COVID-19 on the economy, there is extreme uncertainty in the economic forecasts used by TAWA. The model is also limited in its ability to reflect the step change in the economy due to COVID-19 and the distributional and poverty impacts should be considered indicative comparisons of the different policies. The Treasury considers these results to have medium reliability and medium risk.
